Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the final session! The players are making their way out to the middle now. Usman Khawaja and Nathan McSweeney are the two openers for Australia. Birthday boy, Jasprit Bumrah to start proceedings with the ball. Here we go...
... SECOND INNINGS ...

Right then, India have posted a somewhat competitive total on the board, but as we saw in the first Test, anything can happen in cricket. Australia will feel confident but their batters need to be at their best especially facing Jasprit Bumrah under lights with the pink ball. An exciting last session awaits us and it will be a great battle between two fierce rivals. Join us in a bit for Australia's replay.

The man of the moment, Mitchell Starc is up for a quick chat. He says that the ball was coming out nicely from his hand in this game. Adds that they did not do much wrong in Perth but India played better. Mentions that the pitch is a good one, the ball is moving away and they just wanted to keep the momentum going. Says that as a bowling unit, they need to be patient as there will be some rough patches that you need to get through. End by saying that sometimes the pink ball swings too much sometimes it doesn't, but apart from the first hour, they made most of the conditions.

Australia will be pleased with their bowling performance but will know they missed an opportunity to do even better. Mitchell Starc set the tone with a stunning first-ball wicket, but the team couldn’t fully capitalize, dropping a few chances along the way. It was Starc again who broke through just before Tea and claimed the prized wicket of Virat Kohli, finishing as the standout performer with his maiden five-wicket haul in Tests against India. Scott Boland and Pat Cummins provided solid support, picking up key wickets, but Nitish Kumar Reddy counter-attacked brilliantly, adding crucial runs in the lower order to keep India in the game. Every time, skipper Cummins turned to Starc, he got the wickets and fittingly wrapped things up as well with a six-fer.

India had a nightmare start as Yashasvi Jaiswal was dismissed off the very first ball of the Test match. However, Shubman Gill and KL Rahul weathered the storm early on, countering the fiery spells and stitching together a crucial 50-run partnership. Just when it seemed like India had wrestled back control, both set batters and Virat Kohli fell in quick succession, losing three wickets in the space of four overs. The decision to have Rohit Sharma bat at number 6 didn’t pay off, but Rishabh Pant and Ravichandran Ashwin added vital runs in the middle order. In the midst of the chaos, young sensation Nitish Kumar Reddy once again showcased his class, blending aggression with solid defense to keep India afloat with a breezy 42 off 54.

Australia have wrapped up the Indian innings right on the stroke of Dinner! An outstanding performance with the ball from the hosts and they would have taken this total at the start of the game. Mitchell Starc spearheaded the attack with a fantastic five-wicket haul and proved again why he is the most successful bowler in Day/Night Test matches. Nitish Kumar Reddy was the bright spot for India and played a gritty knock to take them to a fighting first-innings total.

OUT! IN THE AIR AND CAUGHT! Starc wraps this Indian innings with a 6-wicket haul. He bowls from over the stumps and lands it on a good length, just around off. Nitish Kumar Reddy gets forward and looks to go downtown. Goes through the shot but gets no proper timing on it. Nitish's bat twists in his hands and it swirls up in the air. It goes only as far as Travis Head stationed at mid off who takes a very safe catch. He is not dropping those at all. India are bundled out on a paltry 180.

India needs a partnership and the key for them will be the young, Nitish Kumar Reddy who has shown promise in his short stay till now but will need a bit of support from the others as well.

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back for the second session! It is still very overcast out there, but there's no rain around, fortunately. The Australian players take the field and spread out to their respective positions. Rishabh Pant and Rohit Sharma walk out to resume their innings for India. Also, a few of the floodlights are glittering now. And it will be Scott Boland (7-0-24-1) to resume the proceedings with the ball for Australia. Here we go...
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

UPDATE - 6.41 am GMT - There was some rain lurking around in Adelaide and the hessian covers were brought in near the pitch during the break. But, as per Mark Nicholas on-air, the covers are going off now, which is good news and we will have the resumption pretty soon.

Well then, the first session of this Day-Night Test has flown by. While there's been consistent variable bounce which has indeed troubled the batters, the initial lateral movement has notably waned away. All eyes now turn to the post-Tea session, where the artificial lights could add another dimension to the contest. The crucial question is, will the evening conditions aid Australia's bowlers with more swing, or will India's batters build a substantial partnership? Join us back with all the action in a bit. It resumes at 6.40 am GMT.

KL Rahul lived on an edge and got a reprieve twice into his innings. He rode his luck through two significant escapes - first when Scott Boland seemed to have him caught behind only for the delivery to be called a No-Ball, and then when Usman Khawaja failed to hold onto an easy chance in the slips. On the back of these lifelines, KL Rahul was just about getting into the groove. But it was the return of Mitchell Starc that finally broke through and dented the Indian batting order. Dismissing Rahul's resistance first, and also getting the better of Virat Kohli, just a few minutes before the break. And with the well-settled Gill too, dismissed, it reduced India from a comfortable 69/1 to a worrisome 81/4. Slight adjustments in line by the Aussie bowlers garnered them more success as they brought the angle closer to the stumps.

India elected to bat first on an overcast afternoon. Mitchell Starc just provided the best of starts for Australia as he sent the in-form Jaiswal packing on the very first ball of the match. Cummins too, interrogated the batters with some exceptional lines and lengths early on. The ball, however, abruptly lost that lateral movement within the first thirty minutes, and the batters found it a bit easy to play their strokes, with the only odd one deviating and bouncing a tad bit. Gill treated the crowd with some eye-catching drives while KL Rahul was very tentative in his approach from the outset.

TEA, DAY 1 - Session Summary - 23 overs, 82 runs, 4 wickets. 16 balls! That is what it took for the fortunes to flip over towards the hosts as they struck three wickets in that little phase. A breathless first session of play at Adelaide, to say the least. It had everything, the ball going past the edges on several occasions, some exquisite shots, a dropped catch as well. But overall, it was a dominant session for Australia as they managed to go through the Indian top order within the first session.

Commentary.Commentary: Done with the pre-match formalities! Former Australian cricketer, Tim May rings the Bradshaw bell to signal the start of this 2nd Test. The crowd is absolutely buzzing and they cannot wait for the action to begin. Australian players spread out and take their respective field positions. Yashasvi Jaiswal and KL Rahul are the two openers for India. Mitchell Starc has the new pink cherry in his hand and is raring to go. Let's play...

We are not far away from the start of the game, but before that, Ricky Ponting and Harbhajan Singh carry the Border-Gavskar Trophy out to the middle together. They are followed by the players from both sides who line up for their respective national anthems. It will be India's first followed by the Australian national anthem. Also, Australia are wearing black armbands for the 10-year anniversary of Phillip Hughes' passing and the recent passing of former Aussie, Ian Redpath.

PITCH REPORT - Matthew Hayden and Sunil Gavaskar are inspecting the Adelaide pitch. Gavaskar says that a lot of grass has been taken off over the last few days. Also mentions that there's still a bit of grass here and there which means the new ball will help the seamers. Hayden then reckons that conditions are pretty good for the first day and it will start to deteriorate as it progresses.

Pat Cummins, the captain of Australia they would have batted first as well but it's Pink Ball and it might nip around a bit under overcast conditions. Adds that it is nice to get a fresh start and the pink ball can be different to a red ball. Mentions that they were not at their best in the last game, but they have prepared well for this one. Informs they have made just one change as Scott Boland comes in for Hazlewood.

Rohit Sharma, the skipper of India says it looks like a good pitch. Says it is dry with some grass covering as well. Reckons that there will be something for everyone. Adds that he landed in Australia a couple of weeks back. Tells that they played really well in Perth and it is all about carrying that momentum in this match as well. On being asked about whether long breaks between matches help the players, he says that it indeed helps the pacers to rehab and recovery. Informs three changes in the side.

Australia (Playing XI) - Usman Khawaja, Nathan McSweeney, Marnus Labuschagne, Steven Smith, Travis Head, Mitchell Marsh, Alex Carey (WK), Pat Cummins (C), Mitchell Starc, Nathan Lyon, Scott Boland (In place of Josh Hazlewood).

India (Playing XI) - Yashasvi Jaiswal, KL Rahul, Shubman Gill (In place of Devdutt Padikkal), Virat Kohli, Rohit Sharma (C) (In place of Dhruv Jurel), Rishabh Pant (WK), Nitish Kumar Reddy, Ravichandran Ashwin (In place of Washington Sundar), Harshit Rana, Jasprit Bumrah, Mohammed Siraj.
TOSS - It's toss time in Adelaide. Pat Cummins flips the and Rohit Sharma calls it right. India have elected to BAT first.

There's some weather lurking around Adelaide, but the overcast conditions could add another layer of intrigue to this exciting contest and toss could be a major factor in this match. Can India make it 2-0, or will Australia fight back to level the series? Stay tuned - toss and team updates are on the way!

India, despite suffering a humiliating 3-0 defeat to New Zealand at home, delivered a stunning performance to take the lead in this series. They managed it without regular skipper Rohit Sharma, as stand-in captain Jasprit Bumrah led from the front, dismantling the Aussie batting lineup. Virat Kohli's century in the first Test should be a massive confidence booster after a prolonged lean patch, and the return of captain Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill further bolsters the Indian lineup.

Australia's batting has been underwhelming lately, and with David Warner retired, they are still searching for a dependable opener to partner Usman Khawaja. The dip in form of stalwarts like Steven Smith and Marnus Labuschagne is also a concern, but they are known to deliver when the pressure is on. Despite trailing in the series, Australia will draw confidence from their last Pink Ball Test against India here, where they bowled them out for just 36. While they will miss Josh Hazlewood, the bowling attack remains formidable, with skipper Pat Cummins, Mitchell Starc, and Scott Boland ready to challenge the Indian batters once again.

Hello and a warm welcome, everyone! The iconic Adelaide Oval is all set to host a thrilling Pink Ball Test as fierce rivals Australia and India lock horns once again. With the Men in Blue leading the Border-Gavaskar Trophy 1-0 after a stellar performance in the opening Test, the stakes couldn’t be higher. This match carries significant weight in the World Test Championship race, as both teams are determined to secure a win and bolster their chances of making the final.
... DAY 1, SESSION 1 ...

We are back for India's second innings! The players are already out in the middle with the crowd buzzing. Yashasvi Jaiswal and KL Rahul are the two openers for India. Mitchell Starc has the new ball in hand and is raring to go. Here we go...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

Travis Head made the most out of it and smashed a big hundred scoring 140 runs which is currently the difference between the two sides. Earlier it was Nathan McSweeney and Marnus Labuschagne who got through some testing spells under lights and in the morning, but steadied the ship nicely. Marnus answered his critics with a fighting half-century while there were some valuable contributions from Mitchell Starc and Pat Cummins down the order to take the lead of Australia to 157 runs. Their bowlers will be brimming with confidence, especially bowling under lights and India will need to bat their skins out to stay in this contest. Join us in a bit for the second essay.

After getting booed in the final stages of the second session, Mohammed Siraj came back in to wrap up the Australian innings quickly. His send-off to local hero, Travis Head did not go well with the crowd but credit to him for battling it out in the middle and ending up with 4 wickets. Jasprit Bumrah was at his usual best again and picked up four as well while Ravichandran Ashwin and Nitish Kumar Reddy chipped in with one each. It was not easy for the visitors, and dropping a few chances did not help them either, with the most costly being Siraj dropping Head.

OUT! CASTLED! Siraj gets his fourth wicket and wraps up this Australian innings! Siraj stays over the stumps and lands it on a good length, around off and just holds its line. Scott Boland plays at it to work it on the off side but swings inside the line of the ball. It zips past the outside edge and disturbs the off-pole in a flash. Australia end their innings at 337, with a lead of 157 runs.

... DAY 2, SESSION 3 ...

India had a tough grind in this session. Jasprit Bumrah bowled sparingly, battling cramps, while Ravichandran Ashwin was outstanding with the ball, maintaining a tight leash on the scoring. However, Harshit Rana's lack of experience allowed Head to launch a counter-attack. Mohammed Siraj toiled tirelessly and was rewarded, dismissing Alex Carey before claiming the prized wicket of Travis Head. The second new ball brought success right at the end, with Bumrah removing the opposition skipper on the final delivery of the session. The visitors will aim to wrap up the innings quickly, while the Aussies will look to maximize their tally. Join us at 9 am GMT for what promises to be an exciting final session!

Travis Head set the tone early, finding the boundary consistently and keeping the scoreboard ticking. However, wickets kept tumbling at the other end. Mitchell Marsh walked back after edging one he didn’t touch, surprisingly choosing not to review. Alex Carey then joined Head, and the pair stitched together a brisk 72-run partnership, stretching the lead further and taking the game away from the visitors. Head, in scintillating form, smashed his way to a century at his favorite venue against a favored opponent. Mitchell Starc and Pat Cummins chipped in with some powerful strokes, but the skipper fell just before the Dinner break.

With that wicket, the umpires have called for DINNER ON DAY 2! Another session that belonged to Australia, but India had a few positives to take from it as well! Despite losing wickets, the Aussies have strengthened their grip on this game courtesy of a destructive 140 from Travis Head. For India, the other bowlers did step up to support Jasprit Bumrah, but they have conceded a big lead of 152 runs with still two wickets left for the hosts.

The umpires want to have a check for a fair delivery, and it is one as Bumrah has got some part of his feet behind the line. Australia lose their 8th wicket as Cummins departs on 12. And with that, it will be DINNER ON DAY 2!

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks! Well, Australia are firmly in the driving seat as Travis Head's blistering knock has extended their lead to 93 runs now. For India, the lone success came from Ashwin who got the better of Mitchell Marsh earlier in the session. With five wickets still in hand and the dependable Carey partnering Travis Head, the hosts will be pleased enough to go unscathed through this session. Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back for the second session of Day 2! It is a bright and sunny afternoon in Adelaide with a jampacked crowd. The Indian players take their respective fielding positions. Travis Head and Mitchell Marsh stride out to resume their innings for Australia. Ravichandran Ashwin (7-2-22-0) to bowl the first over the session. Here we go...
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

Now, Australia, with the lead at their helm aims to extend it and take the game away from India's reach as they still have six wickets to spare. While India's first aim would be to dent into this partnership and create inroads as quickly as possible as Australia still doesn't have a broad lead. But for that, over-reliance on Bumrah won't work, all the bowlers will have to bring their A-game in the second session, which is known as a perfect time to bat on. Post-Tea session begins at 6.40 am GMT. Stay tuned.

India's bowling attack lost its edge once Bumrah was rotated out. Though Siraj maintained intensity through an extended spell and created occasional chances, a breakthrough proved elusive. The inexperience of Harshit Rana was exposed as he leaked runs consistently, failing to find his rhythm. Meanwhile, Ashwin's threat was neutralized by careful batting on a surface yet to offer significant turn. But just when this Head-Labuschagne alliance was looking more threatening, Nitish Reddy was brought into the attack and broke through this 65-run stand for the fourth wicket. Head though continued on his merry way against his favorite opposition and notched up a fifty in no real time.

India began right on the money with Siraj and Bumrah bowling in tandem. The two pacers interrogated the Aussie overnight batters with some tight lines and lengths. They mixed their lines and lengths well and didn't allow the runs to flow freely in the initial hour. It was Bumrah who ended the resistance of McSweeney and also removed Smith in a quick interval of time. Australia's early struggles gave way to a momentum shift as Travis Head joined the resolute Labuschagne at the crease. Head's arrival injected fresh dynamism into the innings, as he took on the bowling with characteristic aggression. The pair found gaps with regularity, peppering the boundary, and rapidly ate into the deficit.

TEA, DAY 2 - Session Summary - 26 overs, 105 runs, 3 wickets. An entertaining session to be very fair. The first hour belonged to India but the next hour was bossed by the Aussie batters. And since Australia scored runs at a quick pace, it belongs to the hosts. As of now, Australia leads 4 sessions and stands in the pole position, while India still is in search to dominate a session.
Mohammed Siraj bangs this short and around off, Travis Head sways away and tries to ramp it away but fails to connect. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 2!

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Bumrah again opens the door for India! Nathan McSweeney's hard resistance comes to an end and Australia lose their second wicket. Bumrah continues and steams in from over the stumps, uses the crease to his benefit and bowls it from a bit wide angle and slants it on the off-pole, on a hard length. Nathan McSweeney is drawn forward to defend it out, but the ball kisses the surface and just nips away and bounces a bit more. Hence, McSweeney plays inside the line and a healthy outside edge is found. Rishabh Pant does the rest behind the wickets by taking a regulation catch. Bumrah gets his second and McSweeney departs for 39 off 109 balls. Australia trail by 89 runs.

PITCH REPORT - Sunil Gavaskar and Matthew Hayden are inspecting the Day 2 Adelaide surface. Gavaskar says there's a fair bit of grass and the Indian bowlers will aim to take the benefit of the breeze as well. Also adds that Australia has used the roller and its effect would be there for almost an hour or so. Hayden joins him and says that it has still got a lot of live grass and it is a bit spongy and has also started to crack a little bit. Mentions that there's a bit of dust as well and the moisture has just gone away due to the heat. Informs that the conditions are pleasant for both batting and bowling. He further adds that the seamers will have to stay patient and stick to their lines and lengths. Gavaskar says that the bowlers should make the batters play as much as they can and aim at the stumps to get the results.

India, on the other hand, will be disappointed with their batting performance, as the conditions didn’t justify being bowled out for 180. Shubman Gill and KL Rahul showed promise early on, but yet another collapse saw them lose three wickets in just four overs before Tea, completely shifting the momentum. The silver lining was Nitish Kumar Reddy, whose brisk 42 highlighted his growing reliability as an all-rounder. With the ball, the pace attack worked tirelessly and posed a few challenges, but it was the birthday boy, Jasprit Bumrah, who claimed the only Australian wicket. India will look to come out with renewed energy and strike early, but with the pitch improving for batting, the hosts will aim to bat India out of the game. Stay tuned as the action on Day 2 is not far away.

Australia were put into bowl but couldn’t have asked for a better start, with Mitchell Starc striking on the very first ball. He was in sensational form, delivering every time his skipper called on him. Proving once again why he’s the most successful bowler with the Pink Ball, Starc recorded his career-best Test figures of 6/48. The batters then built on the bowlers’ efforts, with Nathan McSweeney and Marnus Labuschagne navigating some testing spells under the lights. By the end of the day, Australia had closed the deficit to just 94 runs, losing only one wicket in the process.

Hello and a warm welcome, everyone! After an enthralling Day 1 of this Day/Night Test, we’re all set for Day 2, where the action promises to be just as exciting. Australia had the upper hand throughout the opening day, despite losing the toss, and will aim to strengthen their grip on the match. India, on the other hand, will need to regroup and make some key adjustments to claw their way back into the contest.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1...

With that, an immersive first day of this Pink Ball Test draws to a close now. A day that well and truly belongs to Australia as they bossed all three sessions of play. Mitchell Starc wreaked havoc with a six-wicket haul, bundling India out for 180 before Dinner. The Aussies then showed their mettle under lights with the bat, losing just one wicket while navigating the tricky new ball period. Though a forgettable day for India, the stand between Gill and Rahul, debutant Nitish Kumar Reddy's gutsy innings, and Bumrah's lone strike offered slim consolation. The stage is now set for Day 2 with Australia eyeing a commanding lead while India desperately needs early breakthroughs to stay in the hunt. Action resumes on Day 2 which begins on December 7, Saturday, at 4 am GMT. Till then, cheers!

The seamers kept finding subtle movement through the air, just enough to whisper past the bat's edge, but their line strayed frequently outside off-stump. This allowed the Australian batters to comfortably let deliveries pass harmlessly. India's pace attack, with Bumrah out of the attack, perhaps missed a trick by not targeting the stumps more frequently. It allowed Marnus and McSweeney to work hard and settle in nicely. The two grew in confidence gradually and formed a solid 62-run stand to see through the day.

Australia could have effectively been a wicket down early, had Pant not grassed the catch behind the wickets. Despite this let-off, the Indian pacers maintained their disciplined attack, generating significant movement to trouble both batters and create chances. Though McSweeney's inexperience was evident in his tentative approach, he managed to survive the testing first hour against the new ball. However, despite all the hard work, Usman Khawaja failed to hang on against Bumrah and that was the solitary loss to the Australian batting order.

The final session began under the lights with Australia taking the crack with the bat. With the new ball doing just enough to beat the edges constantly. Pace duo of Bumrah and Siraj launched a questioning opening spell that kept both Australian openers on their toes. Nathan McSweeney appeared particularly unsettled, displaying visible signs of nerves at the crease. Meanwhile, Khawaja adopted a more measured approach, working the ball around for singles while carefully navigating the threatening new ball.

STUMPS, DAY 1 - Session Summary - 33 overs, 86 runs, 1 wicket. Though runs and overs came at a leisurely pace at Adelaide, the day's cricket proved captivating with plenty of drama unfolding in the middle. The Australian pair of Nathan McSweeney and Marnus Labuschagne go unscathed on Day 1 and the hosts would be the happier sides of the two while heading to the sheds. Australia trail by 94 runs but they do have 9 wickets in hand.

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks! It has been a riveting contest between bat an ball. India have managed to pick up one wicket but their bowlers are not giving away anything to the batters. They will like to get a couple of more scalps before Stumps and put the pressure back on the hosts. Australia have taken a steady approach with Nathan McSweeney getting a bit lucky on a few occasions, but he has stood firmly. Marnus Labuschagne is also blocking out everything and they are just trying to tire out the Indian bowlers. We can expect more of the same from both teams. An exciting phase of cricket awaits us.

OUT! EDGED AND GONE! Who else, it is that man Jasprit Bumrah once again who gets the breakthrough for India. He sets up the batter perfectly here. He angled it in on the previous two balls, but this time gets it to nip away from back of a length and on the fifth stump line. Usman Khawaja is not expecting that, and opens his body, and has a poke at it without moving his feet. Gets an outside edge straight to Rohit Sharma at first slip who makes no mistake. Australia lose their first! Australia are 24/1, trailing by 156 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back to the chase! The Indian players take their fielding positions. Nathan McSweeney and Usman Khawaja are the two openers for Australia with the former taking the guard. Jasprit Bumrah has the new ball to begin the proceedings for India. Here we go...
... FOURTH INNINGS ...

Well then, it's heading towards the conclusion way earlier than anticipated, isn't it? We already know what the result is going to be, but just for the sake of formality, Australia will come out to bat to chase 19 runs. It shouldn't take them more than five overs to do so. Stay tuned as Australia's chase is up next very shortly.

Pat Cummins, the man of the m moment is down for a quick chat. He says that he felt good out there and is happy to get things done early this morning. Adds that the defeat in Perth was a bit overblown and everything seems to be going great and mentions that they love this venue and the crowd has been brilliant and it's been a couple of amazing days.

For Australia, it was a complete bowling display this time around. After Starc's 6-fer in the first innings, it was the skipper Pat Cummins who was the destructor in chief in the second innings. He employed the short ball ploy to perfection and garnered five wickets to his name, while Scott Boland snagged three and Mitchell Starc claimed two to his name. Australia used just three pacers and the Indians were bundled up within a couple of sessions after coming to bat.

With the big guns silenced - Rohit, Gill, Kohli, and Jaiswal all back in the pavilion - it fell to the daring Rishabh Pant to keep India afloat. Though he unleashed some trademark fireworks to chip away at the deficit, day three brought fresh trouble as Starc struck early to remove him. From there, it became a simple battle for survival, with India desperately trying to hang on at the crease. Nitish Kumar Reddy though, held onto his end and entertained the crowd for his stay of 42 runs and helped to clear the deficit. Nitish stood as the highest run-scorer for India in both innings, while the others couldn't even cross their 30s.

180 in the first innings, and 175 in the second. A very disappointing stint for the Indian batters, to say the least. No batter could really get going against this much-improved Australian pace trio. India's batting turned into a nightmare from the get-go as KL Rahul fell early to Cummins' precision. While Jaiswal and Gill tried to weather the storm, Boland's entrance changed everything. He ripped through the batting lineup, claiming Kohli among his victims, as India crumbled to 86/4 in a blink. The bouncy track had India's finest batters dancing to Australia's tune.

Head over there backtracks well and settles under it to take a fine catch and unlike return gifts, Head does not give a return sendoff to Siraj. India are bundled out for 175 in their second innings and Australia need 19 runs to square the series.

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks! Well, Australia is on the verge of leveling this series as they have blown away the Indian batting unit twice, and quite effectively in this Test. This time around, the primary destructor has been Pat Cummins who snagged a 5-fer and has been exceptional since the beginning of this day with his short ball tactics. Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness for Day 3 to get underway as former Aussie pacer and local hero Jason Gillespie rings the bell! The umpires are out in the middle and the players of Australia spread onto the field of play as well. It will be the duo of Rishabh Pant and Nitish Kumar Reddy to resume their overnight stay at the crease. Mitchell Starc with ball in hand is ready to steam in. Let's play...

PITCH REPORT - Mark Nicholas, Matthew Hayden, and Sunil Gavaskar are inspecting the Day 3 surface of Adelaide. Hayden begins and says that it's still a hard surface with a beautiful layer of grass on it. Also mentions the footmarks in line with the stumps. Reckons that Cummins and Boland can bowl in that region all day long. He also thinks that it is still a good batting pitch and India will need to bat well. Gavaskar joins in and says that India needs to score in excess of 250. Also points out the little scratched region where Ashwin could benefit from it. Ends by saying that the batters should give at least something for the bowlers to defend.

Australia’s aim is simple coming into the third day, get the remaining five wickets in the first session itself, and keep India’s lead dwarfed to gain the upper hand. India’s aim will be to surpass the remaining deficit and add as many runs as possible. With Pant still there in the middle, his quick knock can add significant runs to the total. But it’s quite a challenging task from here on and he will need good support from the other end to battle through the session. Is it doable? Quite much. An enthralling third day is on the cards, folks! Brace yourselves.

Will this Test progress on the fourth day? Well, the answer lies with how the Indian batters perform in this first session. Rishabh Pant has looked audacious with his shots, quite characteristic of him. While he has the young Nitish Kumar Reddy partnering him, who has equally been a revelation with the bat. But it’s all about how the remaining batters negotiate against the in-form Aussie pace battery.

India on the other hand, had another forgettable day at the office as the batters couldn’t just get going. There were a few starts from Jaiswal and Gill, but no batter could extend their innings to a substantial score. India’s biggest worry has been the lukewarm form of the two stalwarts - Kohli and Rohit. Kohli’s longing vulnerability outside off stump, and Rohit’s unfamiliar batting position were the reasons for their downfall. And this is why India finds itself in a precarious. With the ball generating extra bite off the deck, the challenge gets bigger and bigger for India, and the remaining batters' temperament will be the key.

Debates in the cricketing circles were just brewing up about whether Pat Cummins had lost his charm with the ball, but he dashed all the critics and found his groove perfectly. Filling in the big shoes of Hazlewood, Scott Boland executed an eye-catching performance that effectively triggered the collapse of the opposition camp. The entire Australian bowling attack including Starc has shown a marked improvement in this Test match, putting aside their underwhelming display from the first game of the series. And have shown why they are a force to be reckoned with when it comes to pink-ball cricket.

Having dominated all six out of six sessions so far, the hosts have outplayed the tourists and it won’t be any exaggeration to say this. They have been brilliant in all facets of the game. It was Marnus Labuschagne who set the tone for Australia and was followed by the bombardment of boundaries by Travis Head who notched up a run-a-ball-century against his favourite opposition and in front of his home crowd. He proved to be a real ‘head’ache to the Indians yet again and broadened the lead further for Australia.

Test cricket in Australia + Sunday showdown = box office entertainment! And this match has been delivering drama by the bucketload for two days straight! On that note, hello and a very warm welcome to our coverage of this Pink Ball Test at Adelaide. Australia holds all the aces in this Day/Night contest and are inching closer to a win, while India has a mountainous task ahead of them.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Entertained enough? Hold onto your seats as this Pink Ball Test progresses into the 'Moving Day'. It is a Sunday and anticipations are high, in fact, more electric as compared to this second day, which was immersive and full of action in itself. Australia is in a commanding position and their aim will be to clinch the remaining wickets and prevent India from taking a broad lead. Whereas, for India, a tough examination awaits on Sunday morning against this quality Aussie pace attack. Their aim should be to weather the first critical hour of play going unscathed and building upon the lead. Still, a mountainous task for the tourists to execute. Day 3 begins on Sunday, December 8 and the first ball will be bowled at 4 am GMT. Till then, cheers!

As things stand, Australia dictated the terms and conditions on this second day. First with the bat, courtesy of the massive contribution by Travis Head, and then with the seamers just not letting the Indian batters form a substantial partnership. As a result, all three sessions go in the favor of the hosts. India, on the other hand, is badly reeling in this game. The only positive for them was the pace tandem of Bumrah and Siraj who shared 8 wickets between them. The batters did not complement those bowling performances and hence, India finds itself in unfamiliar territory, staring a probable defeat. But, in cricket, conclusions cannot be drawn until the last ball has been bowled.

The second hour of play saw the ball repeatedly flirting past the edges, keeping India's batters in constant uncertainty. Though Smith put down a chance, it proved inconsequential as Starc soon had Gill's number. Australia's bowling rotations proved masterful, with each change bringing fresh trouble for the Indians. The variable bounce from the surface only amplified their challenges, making it increasingly difficult for batters to settle in for long stays at the crease. Rishabh Pant tried to keep up the pace of scoring by playing some audacious strokes that kept the crowd entertained. He holds the key for India as they still trail by 29 runs.

Jaiswal and Gill maintained positive intent, keeping the scoreboard moving through a mix of well-placed boundaries and sharp running between wickets. Though Starc and Cummins repeatedly threatened with deliveries that beat the bat's edges, it was Boland who landed a couple of quick blows, first dismissing Jaiswal just as his partnership with Gill was beginning to flourish. Virat Kohli's vulnerability again resurfaced yet again, as he poked at the ball going outside off and nicked it. India was in all sorts of trouble being 66/3.

The final session commenced with emotions at full display and a participating crowd after a sensational play in the second session. Siraj injected in some unplayable deliveries from the outset. He and Bumrah made short work of Australia's lower order, triggering a collapse that saw them lose their last four wickets for just 27 runs, sliding from a comfortable 310/6 to 337 all out. But before that, Australia had already taken the lead of 157 runs. Under the lights, India's response was a bit rusty to begin with as KL Rahul couldn't stay for long and perished too early.

STUMPS, DAY 2 - Session Summary - 26.3 overs, 133 runs, 7 wickets - 379 runs scored in the day! Yes, you read it correctly. What an entertaining day of cricket overall we have had here at the Adelaide Oval. A lively jam-packed crowd, in excess of 50,000 people, and a blockbuster progression of cricket. Australia holds all the aces as we speak as they have well and truly dominated this Pink Ball Test on the back of some pleasing performances.

Commentary.Commentary: Well then, two done, and three chapters remain in this highly anticipated Border-Gavaskar Trophy 2024/25. Australia, with this win, has found that equalizer and this series now hangs right in balance. India, on the other hand, would like to go to the drawing board and assess where things went completely wrong for them in Adelaide. But now, no long rest days for both sides, as the next three Tests will be played back-to-back within a month or so. Both teams have historically displayed remarkable comebacks and this time, it is no different either. India aims a bounceback while Australia would like to continue this winning momentum. Now, back to the red-ball cricket, folks! The caravan now heads towards Brisbane, where the iconic Gabba will host the third Test. It begins on Saturday, December 14 with the first ball scheduled to be bowled at 11.30 pm GMT, the previous day (5 am IST). Till then, cheers, and goodbye!

Pat Cummins, the skipper of Australia says that it has been a great week and they knew they were far away from the team they want to be in Perth. Adds that he wasn't too unhappy with his bowling in Perth and goes on to applaud Mitchell Starc for doing it time and time again for about a decade. On Travis Head, Cummins says that he loves batting here and you could sense it the moment he walked out to bat. Reckons that the first-innings lead was crucial and that helped put pressure on with the ball under lights. Goes on to then applaud Scott Boland for filling in and hopes that Josh Hazlewood is back for the next game.

Rohit Sharma, the captain of India says it has been a disappointing week for them as a team. he appreciates the Australian team and states that they played better cricket. Reckons that they had their chances but were not able to capitalise on them and which ultimately cost them the game. Mentions that what they did in Perth was really special and that they wanted to come here and replicate the same in Adelaide. He then says that every game throws a different challenge. Ends by saying that they are looking forward to the next Test and they will come back stronger in Brisbane.

Travis Head is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH. He starts by saying that it feels nice to get runs again and mentions that it is just another game and it is a tight Test series. Adds that it was a good team performance and nothing was a guarantee and says that he was given the confidence to see the game and play it the way he wanted. Reckons that they picked their moments well and it feels good to do well in front of the home crowd.
The Presentation Ceremony...

Silver linings emerged for India despite the loss. While Bumrah maintained his stellar form, the resurgence of Mohammed Siraj was perhaps the bowling unit's small win - a timely return to rhythm that could prove crucial in the series ahead for India. Though the batting lineup largely faltered, two men stood tall and showed some fight. The ever-adventurous Rishabh Pant and the promising Nitish Kumar Reddy. Young Reddy's gritty display with both bat and ball may have just locked down that coveted all-rounder spot in the lower order.

So, what went wrong for India in this Pink Ball Test? The tourists batted for over 180 overs collectively in Perth, versus just 81 overs in this Test, and failed to cross the 200-run mark. Their batting collapses have been a headache for quite some time now, following that series against New Zealand at home. For Australia, after an underwhelming bowling display in Perth, the pacers came out all guns blazing and scorching to blow away the opposition. Starc’s 6-fer and Cummins’ 5-fer in Adelaide, with Boland’s brilliance added to Australia’s success. But what stood out was a swashbuckling century from Travis Head that took the game way away from India’s clutches.

Cut to Day 3, Pat Cummins didn’t take long enough to run through the Indian lower order. While Pant fell victim to Starc pretty early in the day, Cummins did the clean-up work employing a barrage of short balls which proved highly effective. Although Nitish Kumar Reddy showed some grit towards the backend, it was just too little and too late by that time. But, he did emerge as the leading run-scorer for India, mirroring a quickfire 42 in both innings. Australia had a tiny formality to chase 19 runs and did that without any damage to level the series by 1-1.

However, once Head got out, it triggered a staggering collapse where Australia was reduced to 310/6 to 337 all out. For India, Jasprit Bumrah dismantled the top order effectively, while Mohammed Siraj bowled his heart out, and rolled through the tail of Australia, finally striking through by dismissing Head off a venomous yorker and both of them claimed 4 wickets apiece. Coming to bat, India had a challenging lead of 157 in front of them, but their batting collapse yet again resurfaced as the visitors found themselves badly reeling at 86-4 with the big guns back in the sheds. Pat Cummins and Scott Boland were the architects of this collapse who claimed two each. By the end of the second day, India was effectively reduced to 128/5 with only Pant battling it out alone.

Australia's initial response was cautious with the bat, especially during the challenging twilight period. They scored at a snail's pace initially, but the opening pair of Nathan McSweeney and Usman Khawaja showed resistance until Jasprit Bumrah struck late in the day. Australia resumed Day 2 strongly with Marnus Labuschagne and McSweeney building a solid second-wicket partnership. However, Bumrah's reintroduction brought quick success for India with a couple of breakthroughs. The game's complexion changed dramatically with Travis Head's arrival. The left-hander launched an aggressive counter-attack, racing to a run-a-ball 140. His fearless approach disrupted bowlers' rhythms and toyed around the field, putting India under significant pressure. Head's dominance ensured Australia seized control of the match by taking a decent lead as well.

Now, let's take a quick recap of how things panned out throughout this Test. India's decision to bat first in the Pink Ball Test backfired as they struggled against Australia's pace attack. Despite promising starts from KL Rahul and Shubman Gill, the batting lineup couldn't capitalize. The highlight was a crucial partnership between Nitish Kumar Reddy who impressed with 42 and Ravichandran Ashwin, which helped India reach 180. Mitchell Starc was the wrecker-in-chief, claiming 6 wickets and maintaining his excellent record with the pink ball. Pat Cummins and Scott Boland supported well with two wickets each.

171.5 overs, just 1031 balls, 7 sessions, and just above two days! Also, a staggering stat, is that this is the shortest Test between these two sides, in terms of balls bowled. This is all that it took to get the result in this Pink Ball Test at Adelaide. After a disaster in Perth, Australia came way much improved and stronger at Adelaide. A win by 10 wickets couldn't be a more perfect bounce back for the hosts in this Border-Gavaskar Trophy as they level the series by 1-1.

That's it, Australia have leveled the series! Mohammed Siraj bangs it in short over middle and gets it in at a good height but Usman Khawaja picks up the length early and gets on top of the bounce to pull it away just in front of square leg for a single and what a comeback victory this has been from the hosts. AUSTRALIA WIN BY 10 WICKETS!
